          "id": "financial-literacy-101-l02-c2",
          "title": "Gross Pay vs. Net Pay",
          "content": "When you earn money, it's really important to know the difference between two terms: gross pay and net pay. Let's break it down! Gross pay is the total amount of money you earn before any deductions are taken out. Think of it as your starting point. For example, if you have a job that pays you $100, that $100 is your gross pay. However, there are some things that will be taken out of that amount before you actually get to keep it. This is where net pay comes in! Net pay, which is sometimes called take-home pay, is the money you actually receive after all those deductions. The biggest deduction usually comes from taxes. Taxes are the money that the government collects to help pay for important things like schools, roads, hospitals, and other public services that we all use. So, if you earn $100 and about $20 goes to taxes, your net pay would be around $80. But that’s not all! There can be other deductions too, like health insurance, which helps cover your medical costs, and retirement savings, which is money you set aside for when you’re older and no longer working. When you’re making a budget, it’s super important to use your net pay instead of your gross pay. Why? Because net pay is the actual amount of money you have available to spend on things you need or want. So remember, always plan your budget based on your net pay to make sure you’re spending wisely and saving for the future!\nContext recap: When you earn money, it's really important to know the difference between two terms: gross pay and net pay. Let's break it down! Gross pay is the total amount of money you earn before any deductions are taken out. Think of it as your starting point.\nWhy this matters: Gross Pay vs. Net Pay helps learners in Financial Literacy connect ideas from Financial Literacy Basics to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Keep the explanation friendly and practical.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
