          "id": "financial-literacy-101-l06-c1",
          "title": "Comparison Shopping and Unit Price",
          "content": "When we go shopping, it’s important to be smart about how we spend our money. One great way to do this is by looking at something called the unit price. The unit price helps us understand how much we are paying for each single unit of a product, like how much it costs for one ounce or one pound. This way, we can compare different products and find the best deal!\nLet’s say you want to buy cereal. If Store A has a 12-ounce box of cereal for $3.00, we can find out how much it costs per ounce. To do this, we divide the total price by the number of ounces: $3.00 divided by 12 ounces equals $0.25 per ounce. This means you are paying 25 cents for each ounce of cereal.\nNow, let’s look at Store B. They sell a 20-ounce box of the same cereal for $5.00. To find the unit price here, we do the same calculation: $5.00 divided by 20 ounces equals $0.25 per ounce as well. So, in this case, both stores have the same unit price! This means you can choose either box, depending on which one is easier for you to carry home.\nBut what if Store B had a different price? If they charged $4.00 for the 20-ounce box, we would calculate the unit price again: $4.00 divided by 20 ounces equals $0.20 per ounce. This means you would be paying only 20 cents for each ounce of cereal, which is a better deal than the 25 cents per ounce at Store A!\nTo make sure you are getting the best price, it’s a good idea to check at least three different stores or options before you decide to buy something. Also, keep an eye out for sales! Some sales can really lower the price, while others might just look like a good deal but don’t actually save you money. By being a smart shopper and understanding unit prices, you can make better choices with your money and get the most value for what you spend!\nContext recap: When we go shopping, it’s important to be smart about how we spend our money. One great way to do this is by looking at something called the unit price. The unit price helps us understand how much we are paying for each single unit of a product, like how much it costs for one ounce or one pound. This way, we can compare different products and find the best deal!\nWhy this matters: Comparison Shopping and Unit Price helps learners in Financial Literacy connect ideas from Financial Literacy Basics to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Keep the explanation friendly and practical.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
